Title: Picture Retrieval Systems: A Unifled Perspective and Research Issues  
Author: Venkat N. Gudivada Vijay V. Raghavan 
Note: Contents  
Address: Athens, OH 45701 Lafayette, LA 70504  
Affiliation: Department of Computer Science The Center for Advanced Computer Studies Ohio University University of Southwestern Louisiana  
Abstract: Picture Retrieval (PR) problem is concerned with retrieving pictures that are relevant to users' requests from a large collection of pictures, referred to as the picture database. We use the term picture in a very general context to refer to difierent types of images originating in disparate application areas. The sources for these images range from satellites, diagnostic medical imaging, architectural and engineering drawings, geographic maps, mugshot images of criminals, to family photographs and portraits. A computer system that facilitates picture retrieval is referred to as the Picture Retrieval System (PRS). The application areas that consider picture retrieval as a principal activity are both numerous and disparate. As diverse as the application areas are, there seems to be no consensus as to what a picture retrieval system really is. Consequently, the features of the existing picture retrieval systems have essentially evolved from domain speciflc considerations. The interdisciplinary interest in the PR problem has contributed research results on various aspects of the problem. However, the investigations leading to these research results were carried out quite independently and often from application speciflc concerns. As a consequence, it has become very di-cult to assess the real progress in PR systems. Furthermore, often there is a duplication of research efiort. In this survey paper, we attempt to provide a unifled view of the evolution of PR systems. We trace the origin and developments in this area from a unifled perspective. To achieve this objective, it is essential that we consider image processing functions (which are very often domain dependent) of PR systems and their retrieval functions as two orthogonal issues. We provide a taxonomy under which various approaches to the PR problem can be compared and contrasted. Several representative PR systems are classifled under the proposed taxonomy. Finally, key research problems that need to be addressed for developing truly general purpose PR systems are identifled and future research directions are indicated. 
