uggested [73, 4, 96]. <p> As in the case of spatial similarity, it is desirable that a pictorial data model provide the necessary constructs for specifying logical representations that would support Retrieval by Shape queries. 4.8 Semantic Similarity Retrieval by Semantic Attributes (RSA) represents a major generic retrieval class in picture retrieval applications <ref> [99, 70] </ref>. Simply stated, semantic attributes are those attributes that are used to describe the high-level domain concepts which the images manifest. Speciflcation of semantic attributes necessarily involves some subjectivity, imprecision, and/or uncertainty. Subjectivity arises due to difiering view points of the users about various domain aspects. <p> An exemplar picture may be specifled by assigning semantic attributes to the picture and/or its constituent objects in the sketch pad window (see Query Language/Interface section below) or by simply providing a set of semantic attributes in textual/graphical form <ref> [82, 70] </ref>. Personal Construct Theory [101] from the clinical psychology domain has been used as a knowledge elicitation tool for systematically deriving semantic attributes. An algorithm for RSA has been proposed in [73]. Cognition based approaches to semantic similarity are discussed in [99, 98, 82]. <p> Hence, an automated or semi-automated tool for discovering the set of attributes that are best suited for meeting the retrieval needs of a pictorial database application is essential. A tool for this task based on Personal 32 Construct Theory from the Clinical Psychology domain has been investigated in <ref> [141, 73, 70] </ref>. 4.12 System Architecture We envision a general purpose Picture Retrieval System to feature all of the functionality described above. Such a system will provide uniform access to large, heterogeneous, distributed picture collections.
